<!-- coder-service.archml — a long-running SERVICE coding agent (agent-loop.md §10), the
     M3 companion to the one-shot coder.archml. It shows the design scaling past a single
     task: it takes tasks over a socket, keeps its context bounded, persists across
     restarts, and reports status — all by ADDING optional components, with no change to
     the kernel.

     Run:
       bun meditator.js -a architecture/agents/coder-service.archml
     Then connect to ws://localhost:7640 and send a task (plain text, or
     {"type":"input","data":{"message":"…"}}). The agent works it, calls finish(summary),
     and returns to idle awaiting the next. Ctrl-C sleeps it; its transcript is persisted,
     so a restart resumes mid-task.

     NOTE (local models): m-reason calls the model WITH tools, so a local vLLM must be
     launched with --enable-auto-tool-choice and a matching --tool-call-parser
     (agent-loop.md §12), exactly as m-act already requires. -->
<m-agent name="coder-service"
         interlocutor="user"
         model="voice"
         utilityModel="utility"
         maxSteps="60"
         stopWhen="finish-tool">
  You are a coding agent working inside a sandboxed workspace, serving one request at a
  time. When given a task to carry out, you make it happen: read the code, change it, and
  run commands to check your work, looping until the task is genuinely done. Prefer small,
  verified steps over big guesses. Never claim something works until you have run it and
  seen it pass.
  Not every request is a coding task — sometimes the user just asks a question. Answering
  it fully IS completing the request; do not go looking for work that was not asked for.
  Call finish(summary) as soon as the request is done — whether that means the task is
  complete and verified, or the question is answered — and idle until the next one.

  <!-- No <m-objective>: this agent has no static task. Tasks arrive over the membrane
       (the m-ws socket below) as user turns, and it idles between them. -->

  <!-- The model call. Roomy token budget for tool-calling turns; low temperature. -->
  <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="3000" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>

  <!-- The tools — each self-registers via the bubbling `capability` event (agent-loop.md
       §8), no wiring here. The terminal reuses the sandbox and, inside an agent, returns
       the raw screen as an `observation`; the file tools are contained to the workspace. -->
  <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="60s" network="off"></m-terminal>
  <m-read-file  name="read_file"></m-read-file>
  <m-write-file name="write_file"></m-write-file>
  <m-edit       name="edit"></m-edit>

  <!-- The agent's working memory (agent-loop.md §10): it mirrors the transcript, and when
       it exceeds `budget` it condenses the oldest turns into a summary (reusing m-memory's
       length-loop) while keeping the last `keepRecent` turns verbatim — the standard
       "context window fills up" answer, as one optional component. It also persists the
       transcript to the agent's home, so a restarted service resumes mid-task. -->
  <m-context name="context" budget="24000" keepRecent="8"></m-context>

  <!-- A pure stall observer (agent-loop.md §9): nudges then halts a repeated action. -->
  <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>

  <!-- Status out (agent-loop.md §10): republishes the agent's status as a `report` topic
       and logs each state change, so a supervisor or the Studio can follow it. -->
  <m-report name="status" every="1"></m-report>

  <!-- Tasks in: the membrane. Under an <m-agent>, m-ws is a TASK PORT — inbound client
       input becomes a `user` turn, and the agent's status is broadcast back. -->
  <m-ws name="ws" port="7640"></m-ws>
</m-agent>
